WEBVTT

00:00.166 --> 00:00.199
Ge

00:00.200 --> 00:00.232
Get

00:00.233 --> 00:00.265
Get in

00:00.266 --> 00:00.299
Get in a

00:00.300 --> 00:00.332
Get in all

00:00.333 --> 00:00.366
Get in all t

00:00.367 --> 00:00.399
Get in all tho

00:00.400 --> 00:00.432
Get in all those

00:00.433 --> 00:00.466
Get in all those n

00:00.467 --> 00:00.499
Get in all those noo

00:00.500 --> 00:00.566
Get in all those nooks

00:00.567 --> 00:00.599
Get in all those nooks
an

00:00.600 --> 00:00.632
Get in all those nooks
and

00:00.633 --> 00:00.666
Get in all those nooks
and cr

00:00.667 --> 00:00.699
Get in all those nooks
and cran

00:00.700 --> 00:00.733
Get in all those nooks
and cranni

00:00.734 --> 00:00.766
Get in all those nooks
and crannies

00:00.767 --> 00:00.799
Get in all those nooks
and crannies,

00:00.800 --> 00:00.833
Get in all those nooks
and crannies, Mr

00:00.834 --> 00:00.866
Get in all those nooks
and crannies, Mr.

00:00.867 --> 00:00.899
Get in all those nooks
and crannies, Mr. Di

00:00.900 --> 00:00.933
Get in all those nooks
and crannies, Mr. Digb

00:00.934 --> 00:01.935
Get in all those nooks
and crannies, Mr. Digby!

00:02.035 --> 00:03.136
Your skin will thank you.

00:03.236 --> 00:04.204
(Quietly) We all will.

00:04.304 --> 00:05.505
Day shift needs
completed T-Sheets

00:05.605 --> 00:06.940
on every patient

00:07.040 --> 00:08.341
and to write on the board
what tests are pending

00:08.441 --> 00:09.809
so nothing falls
through the cracks

00:09.909 --> 00:11.411
while we wait
to come back online.

00:11.511 --> 00:13.546
Woman: You have reached The
Pittsburgh Neuroscience Group.

00:13.646 --> 00:14.814
This is Dr. Al-Hashimi.

00:14.914 --> 00:16.583
I'm a patient
of Dr. Fairgraves.

00:16.683 --> 00:17.684
I need to speak to him.

00:17.784 --> 00:18.818
Duke, do not go anywhere.

00:18.918 --> 00:19.886
You are next up.

00:19.986 --> 00:21.187
I'm gonna
deliver you myself.

00:21.287 --> 00:23.056
I'm starting to feel like
a hostage in this place.

00:23.156 --> 00:24.424
How do you think I feel?

00:24.524 --> 00:26.259
You treated her outside
the ED on PTMC's dime

00:26.359 --> 00:27.994
right when we're
in the middle of crisis mode

00:28.094 --> 00:29.429
and we need all hands
on deck.

00:29.529 --> 00:31.297
Is this a panic attack
because of your mommy issues?

00:31.398 --> 00:32.499
What? No.

00:32.599 --> 00:34.167
I don't need the
fuckin' liability! Go home.

00:34.267 --> 00:35.502
Please,
for the love of God,

00:35.602 --> 00:37.170
can you just go wait
over there in the room

00:37.270 --> 00:38.538
with your detainees

00:38.638 --> 00:40.106
so I don't lose any more
patients or staff.

00:40.206 --> 00:41.674
You having some
pain again, Mr. Green?

00:41.775 --> 00:43.209
Ultrasound showed
dilated ureter

00:43.309 --> 00:44.511
and mild
left hydronephrosis.

00:44.611 --> 00:47.113
- What about the aorta?
- I didn't look at the aorta.

00:47.213 --> 00:48.648
Orlando,
where are you going?

00:48.748 --> 00:50.984
I can't add thousands of dollars
to the 100 grand I already owe.

00:51.084 --> 00:52.552
You stay,
and I'll get together everything

00:52.652 --> 00:53.553
you'll need at home.

00:53.653 --> 00:55.288
Unwitnessed fall
from the warehouse catwalk

00:55.388 --> 00:56.689
where he works
as a security guard.

00:56.790 --> 00:58.258
Oh, my God.

01:10.670 --> 01:13.606
[indistinct chatter]

01:15.442 --> 01:17.076
- You know this guy?
- Orlando Diaz.

01:17.077 --> 01:18.844
We were treating him
for DKA when he eloped.

01:18.845 --> 01:20.312
- How far did he fall?
- 20 feet or so.

01:20.313 --> 01:22.247
- Anyone see him pass out?
- No.

01:22.248 --> 01:24.249
They went looking for him after
he didn't answer his radio.

01:24.250 --> 01:25.451
- Pupils equal but sluggish.

01:25.452 --> 01:26.952
- He left against
medical advice.

01:26.953 --> 01:30.689
- On my count, three, two, one.
[grunts]

01:30.690 --> 01:33.092
- Dr. Ellis on the case.
Day shift, we got this.

01:33.093 --> 01:35.394
- I'm staying.
- Continuity of care.

01:35.395 --> 01:36.862
Dr. Al-Hashimi,
why don't you go cover

01:36.863 --> 01:38.063
sign-out rounds with Dr. Abbot?

01:38.064 --> 01:39.398
Shen, you too.
- Got it.

01:39.399 --> 01:41.500
- OK, let me know
if you need anything.

01:41.501 --> 01:44.169
- Lungs are up bilaterally.
- Pelvis is stable.

01:44.170 --> 01:48.107
Right tib-fib hematoma,
deformed right forearm.

01:48.108 --> 01:50.042
- Ruptured TM on the left
with sero-sanguinous fluid.

01:50.043 --> 01:51.710
- That means
basilar skull fracture.

01:51.711 --> 01:53.679
- We've got a diabetic patient,
20-foot fall.

01:53.680 --> 01:55.981
- BP 204 over 98, pulse 56.

01:55.982 --> 01:57.516
- Dr. Mohan, what do those
numbers indicate?

01:57.517 --> 01:59.318
- I'm trying
to treat the patient.

01:59.319 --> 02:00.586
- It's the Cushing's reflex.

02:00.587 --> 02:02.688
- From increased
intracranial pressure.

02:02.689 --> 02:05.124
- Yeah, we need to get him
to CT right away.

02:05.125 --> 02:06.725
- No free fluid in the belly.

02:06.726 --> 02:10.129
- Any family to notify?
- Wife and three kids.

02:10.130 --> 02:12.231
- Is there a card
to sign for Robby?

02:12.232 --> 02:14.199
- No, he said
no card, no presents.

02:14.200 --> 02:15.801
- Oh. Was there a cake?

02:15.802 --> 02:17.236
- Oh, he didn't want
that either.

02:17.237 --> 02:19.304
- That sucks.
I need some cake.

02:19.305 --> 02:21.406
- Patient was injured
when they raided a restaurant.

02:21.407 --> 02:23.242
- And they actually
arrested the nurse?

02:23.243 --> 02:25.711
- With a takedown and zip ties.
- Damn.

02:25.712 --> 02:27.913
- Crus, you, uh, know
the computer downtime drill?

02:27.914 --> 02:29.381
- Yeah, no biggie.

02:29.382 --> 02:31.016
I prefer to treat 'em
without labs and X-rays.

02:31.017 --> 02:32.518
Welcome back.

02:32.519 --> 02:34.319
- If you do have orders
for labs and X-rays,

02:34.320 --> 02:36.421
clipboards go here.

02:36.422 --> 02:39.258
If it's just
nursing orders, here.

02:39.259 --> 02:41.126
- Please write neatly,
for God's sake.

02:41.127 --> 02:43.562
- Oh, Monica, this is Nazely,
new intern.

02:43.563 --> 02:46.466
- I don't need to know that.
- So nice to meet you.

02:47.467 --> 02:49.201
- Looks like you and me, Jack.

02:49.202 --> 02:50.802
- Yeah, who's our senior?

02:50.803 --> 02:53.906
- Dr. Henderson.
- Excellent.

02:53.907 --> 02:55.641
Night shift's on Crus control.

02:55.642 --> 02:57.910
- You hear
ICE brought us a patient?

02:57.911 --> 02:59.545
- Oh, yeah?
How'd that go?

02:59.546 --> 03:00.812
- There was some
collateral damage.

03:00.813 --> 03:02.314
They arrested Jesse.

03:02.315 --> 03:04.249
- For what?
- Assaulting a federal officer.

03:04.250 --> 03:05.851
- Are you fucking kidding me?

03:05.852 --> 03:07.219
- Oh, Dr. Al-Hashimi,

03:07.220 --> 03:09.388
this is Nazely Toomarian--
new intern.

03:09.389 --> 03:12.525
[both speaking Armenian]

03:16.196 --> 03:18.096
- OK, everybody,
let's huddle up.

03:18.097 --> 03:19.431
- Before we start,

03:19.432 --> 03:21.133
let me address
the elephant in the room.

03:21.134 --> 03:22.901
For those of you
who don't know,

03:22.902 --> 03:24.369
Jesse tried to intervene

03:24.370 --> 03:26.238
when a federal agent
was handling his patient,

03:26.239 --> 03:28.440
and both he and the patient
were taken away by ICE.

03:28.441 --> 03:30.242
- Did he punch the guy?
- No.

03:30.243 --> 03:32.578
He put out a hand to stop him,
made physical contact.

03:32.579 --> 03:34.213
- [softly] It was a little bit
more than that.

03:34.214 --> 03:35.714
- The hospital lawyers
are on the case,

03:35.715 --> 03:38.183
and we will brief the staff
every 12 hours

03:38.184 --> 03:39.785
at sign-out rounds
with an official update.

03:39.786 --> 03:42.421
- In the meantime,
don't feed the rumor mill.

03:42.422 --> 03:44.623
- You may have also heard
that new grad nurse Emma here

03:44.624 --> 03:47.226
was assaulted by a patient.
- I--I'm fine.

03:47.227 --> 03:48.860
- Please don't forget
"code hula hoop,"

03:48.861 --> 03:50.195
and with risky patients,

03:50.196 --> 03:52.464
always keep a path
to the door clear.

03:52.465 --> 03:54.199
- Sounds like
one hell of a day.

03:54.200 --> 03:56.068
And we're still dealing
with downtime,

03:56.069 --> 03:58.170
so day shift should brief
night residents

03:58.171 --> 03:59.204
about the protocol--
[clicking]

03:59.205 --> 04:00.572
[crowd murmuring]
- Hey!

04:00.573 --> 04:01.873
- Oh, all right!

04:01.874 --> 04:04.276
[applause]
- Oh, thank God.

04:04.277 --> 04:05.644
- Yeah, not so fast.

04:05.645 --> 04:07.579
Every chart
from the last five hours

04:07.580 --> 04:09.948
needs to be scanned into
the Electronic Health Record

04:09.949 --> 04:12.050
and checked for accuracy...

04:12.051 --> 04:14.186
- Um, whose job is that?
- Day shift.

04:14.187 --> 04:15.988
- With a completed
and signed T-sheet.

04:15.989 --> 04:17.723
- Are you kidding me?
- That's gonna take forever.

04:17.724 --> 04:19.491
- We will set up stations
for scanning.

04:19.492 --> 04:21.393
OK, everybody,
let's get moving.

04:21.394 --> 04:23.428
- Triage is 20 behind.
Gotta help 'em clean up.

04:23.429 --> 04:24.830
I'm skipping rounds.

04:24.831 --> 04:26.531
- Consider yourself lucky.

04:26.532 --> 04:29.234
- Should we join them?
- [sighs]

04:29.235 --> 04:30.869
Might as well
witness the magic.

04:30.870 --> 04:33.205
It's like changing of the guard
at Buckingham Palace.

04:33.206 --> 04:35.107
- Except we're allowed
to smile.

04:35.108 --> 04:37.209
- "Smile though
your heart is aching."

04:37.210 --> 04:38.377
[machine beeping]

04:38.378 --> 04:39.444
- Plain films, right tib-fib

04:39.445 --> 04:41.413
and right forearm after CT.

04:41.414 --> 04:43.448
- Got the chem-8.
Blood sugar's 284.

04:43.449 --> 04:46.118
- That's not too bad.
Potassium looks good.

04:46.119 --> 04:48.320
- Mm-hmm.
Anion gap's up at 14.

04:48.321 --> 04:49.488
- It was 24 this morning.

04:49.489 --> 04:51.223
He's definitely improving.

04:51.224 --> 04:52.524
- The DKA is resolving.

04:52.525 --> 04:54.259
- So what made him pass out?

04:54.260 --> 04:56.194
- It's hot as hell out there.

04:56.195 --> 04:58.330
He could have been dehydrated
from sweating.

04:58.331 --> 05:01.767
Or he could have had
an N-STEMI or a posterior CVA.

05:01.768 --> 05:03.303
- Ready to roll.

05:04.837 --> 05:07.572
- I can babysit him at CT.
- Thank you.

05:07.573 --> 05:09.842
- I'll stay
in case he needs the OR.

05:11.778 --> 05:13.712
- Hey, we're back up.

05:13.713 --> 05:15.547
- It's about time.

05:15.548 --> 05:17.182
- Ooh, Robby.
- Yeah.

05:17.183 --> 05:19.251
- I got intel on where
ICE has taken Jesse.

05:19.252 --> 05:20.519
- Intel from who?

05:20.520 --> 05:22.454
- Uh, my brother-in-law's
a cop.

05:22.455 --> 05:24.756
So he'll be processed
at DHS Southside

05:24.757 --> 05:27.326
and then transferred
to ICE detention in Clearfield.

05:27.327 --> 05:28.660
- Clearfield?
That's two hours away.

05:28.661 --> 05:30.195
- Mm-hmm.

05:30.196 --> 05:32.297
- OK, I'll let
the hospital attorneys know.

05:32.298 --> 05:34.099
- How are you doing, Oliver?
- Alive and kicking.

05:34.100 --> 05:35.500
- Uh, Mr. Haas.

05:35.501 --> 05:37.769
Pulmonary edema
after missed dialysis,

05:37.770 --> 05:40.372
now stable with his son Mason
at the bedside.

05:40.373 --> 05:42.007
- Hello.
- I'm Dr. Shen.

05:42.008 --> 05:43.208
I'll be back.

05:43.209 --> 05:44.276
- Dialysis tech says

05:44.277 --> 05:45.977
I'm off the machine at 10:42.

05:45.978 --> 05:48.146
- Hit the call light,
and I'll come running.

05:48.147 --> 05:50.383
- South 21 next...

05:52.185 --> 05:54.086
Mr. Digby.

05:54.087 --> 05:55.554
- J-just Digby.

05:55.555 --> 05:57.356
- Dr. Mohan's patient.

05:57.357 --> 05:59.491
Forearm cellulitis,
admit med-surge.

05:59.492 --> 06:01.126
Awaiting a bed.
- I can take him.

06:01.127 --> 06:02.994
- Sold to Dr. Toomarian.

06:02.995 --> 06:05.330
Moving right along.

06:05.331 --> 06:07.132
- Get enough to eat?

06:07.133 --> 06:09.534
We'll be back.

06:09.535 --> 06:13.038
- Lillian Stegman.
Tweaked her knee water-skiing.

06:13.039 --> 06:15.006
- Doing a 360
off a 5-foot ramp.

06:15.007 --> 06:16.408
- Ooh, respect.

06:16.409 --> 06:17.843
- X-rays ordered in triage.

06:17.844 --> 06:19.111
- That was hours ago.

06:19.112 --> 06:21.279
- Ma'am,
I'm Dr. Crus Henderson.

06:21.280 --> 06:23.548
Let's get you home real fast.

06:23.549 --> 06:25.217
- That would be wonderful.
- OK, heading to North.

06:25.218 --> 06:26.952
- Thank you.

06:26.953 --> 06:29.588
- Looks like our first scanning
station is almost ready.

06:29.589 --> 06:32.290
Whitaker, Santos, after rounds,
this will be your post.

06:32.291 --> 06:35.026
- Seriously?
- For... how long?

06:35.027 --> 06:37.062
- Till we mop up this mess.

06:37.063 --> 06:38.697
And away we go.

06:38.698 --> 06:40.999
- All right,
now you know everything

06:41.000 --> 06:42.134
there is to know about rounds.

06:42.135 --> 06:43.235
Fascinating, right?

06:43.236 --> 06:45.504
- Uh... yeah.

06:45.505 --> 06:47.707
- Here, I got something
better for you.

06:49.509 --> 06:52.411
So, Digby, we're gonna find you
some new clothes,

06:52.412 --> 06:54.179
but my friend Emma and I
wondered if you'd like

06:54.180 --> 06:56.648
to get cleaned up a bit first.

06:56.649 --> 06:58.483
- I already had a shower.

06:58.484 --> 07:00.085
- I know, and you look good.

07:00.086 --> 07:02.220
But the offer also comes
with a shave and a haircut,

07:02.221 --> 07:03.455
if you're interested.

07:03.456 --> 07:04.589
No pressure--like I said,

07:04.590 --> 07:05.858
you already look great.

07:07.293 --> 07:10.162
- Sure, I guess.
- Fantastic.

07:10.163 --> 07:12.230
All right, kid, fill that basin
with some warm water

07:12.231 --> 07:13.900
and lather him up.

07:16.836 --> 07:19.271
- Hey, stay safe out there.
- Back at you in here.

07:19.272 --> 07:21.373
- Hey, Cary.

07:21.374 --> 07:23.475
You were on scene
with Orlando, right?

07:23.476 --> 07:25.911
Did you notice anything
about his fall?

07:25.912 --> 07:27.446
- Like what?

07:27.447 --> 07:30.515
- Like, um, if there was
a break in the railing

07:30.516 --> 07:33.518
or if there were
security cameras?

07:33.519 --> 07:35.187
- Too busy working on the guy--

07:35.188 --> 07:37.689
IV, intubation,
backboard, splint.

07:37.690 --> 07:38.690
- Thanks.

07:38.691 --> 07:40.425
- Oh, two names is a start.

07:40.426 --> 07:42.160
Pretty soon, we'll retire
the clipboards.

07:42.161 --> 07:43.428
- Baby Jane Doe in Pedes?

07:43.429 --> 07:45.430
- Uh, yeah, abandoned

07:45.431 --> 07:48.033
in the waiting room bathroom
at 7:30 a.m.

07:48.034 --> 07:50.569
- Safe haven drop-off?
- No, she's too old for that.

07:50.570 --> 07:52.437
At least two months.
- I'll take her.

07:52.438 --> 07:54.606
- Awaiting foster placement
by CYF.

07:54.607 --> 07:56.842
- What if the mom comes back?
- Call the cops.

07:56.843 --> 07:58.376
- Day shift,
get to work scanning.

07:58.377 --> 07:59.878
Night shift, the room numbers

07:59.879 --> 08:02.013
on top of the dry-erase board
need a doctor.

08:02.014 --> 08:05.050
- Who's in BH-1?
- Psych hold, danger to self.

08:05.051 --> 08:06.485
- What's the story?

08:06.486 --> 08:08.386
- Doctors King and Langdon
were on the case.

08:08.387 --> 08:10.622
- It's a sad story--
she says her 5-year-old

08:10.623 --> 08:12.390
snuck into the back seat
of the car to take a nap.

08:12.391 --> 08:14.092
- Heat stroke.

08:14.093 --> 08:16.461
- Mom was extremely distraught.
Walked out into traffic.

08:16.462 --> 08:18.163
- Grady Barnhill, wheezing

08:18.164 --> 08:19.631
and not responding
to albuterol.

08:19.632 --> 08:21.566
Pulse ox 87. His mother, Naomi.

08:21.567 --> 08:23.768
- OK, Trauma Two's open.
- On our way.

08:23.769 --> 08:26.338
Uh, Mom, history of asthma?
- His whole life.

08:26.339 --> 08:28.440
Never this bad.
- Barely moving air.

08:28.441 --> 08:31.042
- Using all his
accessory muscles.

08:31.043 --> 08:32.510
- Call RT!

08:32.511 --> 08:35.280
Uh, continuous nebs,
20 milligrams an hour.

08:35.281 --> 08:36.748
- We have a home nebulizer.

08:36.749 --> 08:39.718
I've been giving him
albuterol every hour.

08:39.719 --> 08:40.685
- Ready?

08:40.686 --> 08:43.655
On my count, one, two, three.

08:43.656 --> 08:45.156
- Does he take
any other medications?

08:45.157 --> 08:46.658
- Just the albuterol.

08:46.659 --> 08:48.193
He used to be on montelukast
and Symbicort.

08:48.194 --> 08:49.761
- Why did you stop that?

08:49.762 --> 08:51.763
- Because he lost his Medicaid
two months ago.

08:51.764 --> 08:53.565
- He's so tight,
nothing's getting through.

08:53.566 --> 08:55.200
- Mel, EpiPen.
- On it.

08:55.201 --> 08:56.735
- 0.3 milligrams.

08:56.736 --> 08:59.804
- That may open his lungs
so the nebs can work.

08:59.805 --> 09:01.940
- All right, Grady,
shot in the thigh.

09:01.941 --> 09:04.109
- [grunts]

09:04.110 --> 09:06.912
[beeping]

09:06.913 --> 09:08.647
- Hey.

09:08.648 --> 09:10.248
- Something to scan?

09:10.249 --> 09:11.683
- Critical labs on North Three.

09:11.684 --> 09:13.318
- Oh, it's, uh--
it's not my patient.

09:13.319 --> 09:14.687
- She's about to be.

09:16.522 --> 09:18.823
- I'm, uh--
I'm off the clock, so...

09:18.824 --> 09:21.560
- These were ordered
three hours ago from triage,

09:21.561 --> 09:23.862
so, technically,
she is a day-shift patient.

09:23.863 --> 09:25.297
Just get the intern started.

09:25.298 --> 09:26.731
I got a meeting upstairs
with admin

09:26.732 --> 09:28.767
to get things back on track.

09:28.768 --> 09:30.468
- Sorry.
Everyone else is tied up.

09:30.469 --> 09:31.836
- That's OK.

09:31.837 --> 09:33.171
How'd you get stuck
on night shift

09:33.172 --> 09:34.306
for your first rotation?

09:34.307 --> 09:35.740
- Just lucky, I guess.

09:35.741 --> 09:37.275
- Yeah, if you like
a good horror movie.

09:37.276 --> 09:38.643
- [chuckles]

09:38.644 --> 09:40.579
- Where was med school?
- Uh, UC Irvine.

09:40.580 --> 09:42.447
- California, right?
- Yep.

09:42.448 --> 09:43.615
- Pittsburgh's
a little different.

09:43.616 --> 09:44.749
- Yeah, a lot more humidity.

09:44.750 --> 09:45.850
- Yeah, that'll go away

09:45.851 --> 09:47.752
with your first foot of snow.

09:47.753 --> 09:50.655
Uh, hi, Mrs. Davis.

09:50.656 --> 09:52.624
I am Dr. McKay.
This is Doctor...

09:52.625 --> 09:54.960
- Toomarian.
- Hello.

09:54.961 --> 09:58.029
- Uh, your labs show a lot
of inflammation in your liver.

09:58.030 --> 10:01.333
- Is that why I'm so nauseated?
- Definitely, yeah.

10:01.334 --> 10:04.569
Have you, um, noticed a change
in your skin coloration?

10:04.570 --> 10:06.638
- I've been using
this bronzing cream

10:06.639 --> 10:09.140
so I don't look like a ghost
in my bathing suit.

10:09.141 --> 10:11.109
- Do you remember
the name of the bronzer?

10:11.110 --> 10:12.711
It could have a chemical
that can cause--

10:12.712 --> 10:14.746
- Oh, no, no,
it's 100% natural.

10:14.747 --> 10:17.983
It's DHA from sugar beets.
- OK.

10:17.984 --> 10:20.118
- Why would my liver
be inflamed?

10:20.119 --> 10:22.120
- Uh, there's a lot
of possibilities.

10:22.121 --> 10:24.089
- Are you taking any
prescription medications?

10:24.090 --> 10:25.123
- Not a single one.

10:25.124 --> 10:26.658
- Tylenol?
- God, no.

10:26.659 --> 10:28.860
- We have to ask everybody
about injection drug use.

10:28.861 --> 10:29.828
- Never.

10:29.829 --> 10:31.529
- Raw clams or oysters?

10:31.530 --> 10:33.431
- I'm a vegan.

10:33.432 --> 10:35.567
- One step at a time, OK?

10:35.568 --> 10:36.836
We'll be back.

10:38.070 --> 10:40.105
- Digby, Haas,
now on the big board.

10:40.106 --> 10:41.172
- Progress.

10:41.173 --> 10:42.173
- So he's just been waiting

10:42.174 --> 10:43.742
in the hall the whole time?

10:43.743 --> 10:46.712
OK, well, can you maybe
get to him next?

10:48.014 --> 10:50.015
Thank you. [sighs]

10:50.016 --> 10:51.816
Duke goes to CT,
and they bump him.

10:51.817 --> 10:54.352
- Yeah, he may end up
waiting for hours over there.

10:54.353 --> 10:56.755
- Oh, look at that.
7:15 already.

10:56.756 --> 10:58.790
- Just a few more loose ends
to tie up.

10:58.791 --> 11:01.926
- You got more loose ends
than a macramé wall hanging.

11:01.927 --> 11:04.162
My mom had one.
Took up the whole goddamn wall.

11:04.163 --> 11:05.964
Seriously, you should
think about signing out

11:05.965 --> 11:07.732
and hitting the road.
- Yeah, maybe you should too.

11:07.733 --> 11:09.567
Oh, that's right,
you sent Lena home.

11:09.568 --> 11:11.236
Are you planning on
calling in a replacement,

11:11.237 --> 11:13.171
or are you just gonna work
till sunrise?

11:13.172 --> 11:14.606
- If I have to.

11:14.607 --> 11:16.708
- Oh, so you get to go
the extra mile,

11:16.709 --> 11:19.210
and the rest of us just get
accused of being martyrs.

11:19.211 --> 11:20.613
- Robby.
- Excuse me.

11:22.548 --> 11:24.516
What's the word?
- No subdural, no epidural.

11:24.517 --> 11:26.518
- Diffuse brain swelling
with effacement

11:26.519 --> 11:28.053
and compression
of the ventricles.

11:28.054 --> 11:30.321
- C-spine?
Chest-abdomen-pelvis?

11:30.322 --> 11:32.657
- Uh, left pulmonary contusion,
no intra-abdominal hemorrhage.

11:32.658 --> 11:33.792
- Which means I'm off the hook.

11:33.793 --> 11:35.226
I'll send Neurosurgery down.

11:35.227 --> 11:37.796
- If he doesn't need the OR,
why Neurosurgery?

11:37.797 --> 11:39.297
- Wait and see.
- Let's get busy.

11:39.298 --> 11:40.565
CVP and an art line.

11:40.566 --> 11:43.668
- Orlando.
Orlando, squeeze my hand.

11:43.669 --> 11:46.037
[beeping]
Open your eyes.

11:46.038 --> 11:48.640
- We already know his GCS
is going to be three.

11:48.641 --> 11:50.675
- Hey, Javadi,
anti-seizure prophylaxis?

11:50.676 --> 11:52.677
- Keppra, 20 migs per kilo.
- Mixing it now.

11:52.678 --> 11:54.312
- Gotta get this brain swelling
down, Samira.

11:54.313 --> 11:55.314
How we gonna do that?

11:56.615 --> 11:58.149
Samira?
- What?

11:58.150 --> 12:01.486
- We have to lower
the intracranial pressure.

12:01.487 --> 12:03.088
- Mannitol.
- Not the best.

12:03.089 --> 12:04.489
Can cause diuresis
and hypotension.

12:04.490 --> 12:05.857
- Then hypertonic saline.

12:05.858 --> 12:08.359
- 23%.
50 cc's through a central line.

12:08.360 --> 12:10.261
[beeping]

12:10.262 --> 12:11.763
- Still tight as a drum.

12:11.764 --> 12:12.864
- Five minutes since the epi.

12:12.865 --> 12:14.365
- He can have one more EpiPen.

12:14.366 --> 12:15.967
- Sats are borderline, 87.

12:15.968 --> 12:17.502
- How about BiPap?
10 over 5.

12:17.503 --> 12:19.671
- Yes, with in-line nebs.

12:19.672 --> 12:21.406
- All right, Grady,
shot number two.

12:21.407 --> 12:23.708
- Might as well throw in
some magnesium, 50 per kilo.

12:23.709 --> 12:24.943
- I'm sorry.
He's not ventilating.

12:24.944 --> 12:26.411
We should be ready to intubate.

12:26.412 --> 12:27.779
- With an asthma patient?

12:27.780 --> 12:29.581
There's a high risk
of cardiac arrest.

12:29.582 --> 12:31.850
- Naomi, has he ever been put
on a breathing machine before?

12:31.851 --> 12:33.485
- Never.
- Hospitalized?

12:33.486 --> 12:35.587
- No, we could always break him
with the Symbicort.

12:35.588 --> 12:36.988
- We're gonna give
the current treatment

12:36.989 --> 12:39.157
a few more minutes to help him
turn the corner.

12:39.158 --> 12:42.127
[machines beeping]

12:42.128 --> 12:44.195
- I could probably
do this myself

12:44.196 --> 12:45.497
now that my cast is off.

12:45.498 --> 12:47.432
- Oh, that's OK.

12:47.433 --> 12:49.101
I don't mind.

12:52.972 --> 12:54.940
- How long have you
been a nurse?

12:56.342 --> 12:58.010
- This is my first day.

13:00.679 --> 13:02.782
- You're doing really good.

13:04.583 --> 13:06.185
- Thank you.

13:10.089 --> 13:11.890
- Oh, shit, you OK?
- Yeah.

13:11.891 --> 13:13.525
There's water on the floor.

13:13.526 --> 13:14.893
- Sorry!
I--I might have spilled.

13:14.894 --> 13:16.327
- Yeah, no worries.

13:16.328 --> 13:18.463
We're gonna have to sort
these all by patient

13:18.464 --> 13:20.331
before we scan them.

13:20.332 --> 13:22.867
- Is, uh, Joy still around?

13:22.868 --> 13:25.603
- I heard she left at 6:59.

13:25.604 --> 13:27.505
- Smart girl.
- Mm-hmm.

13:27.506 --> 13:29.808
- You know what? Find Ogilvie.
He's such an ass-kisser.

13:29.809 --> 13:31.509
He might stay and scan
all the charts himself.

13:31.510 --> 13:33.645
- Oh, he, uh, scrubbed in
in the OR,

13:33.646 --> 13:35.547
scrubbed in
on the ruptured triple-A.

13:35.548 --> 13:37.115
- Oh, the kidney stone
that wasn't.

13:37.116 --> 13:39.051
That'll be four hours at least.

13:40.953 --> 13:44.489
So are you still going
to Amy's after work?

13:44.490 --> 13:46.257
- Yeah, maybe just
for tonight,

13:46.258 --> 13:48.761
after Robby briefs me
on all the house stuff.

13:49.695 --> 13:51.262
- Sounds fun.

13:51.263 --> 13:52.630
- [scoffs]

13:52.631 --> 13:54.566
When he asked,
it was hard to say no.

13:54.567 --> 13:56.135
- Sure. [sighs]

13:58.103 --> 14:00.405
It's gonna be very weird
without him here.

14:00.406 --> 14:01.840
- Yeah.

14:01.841 --> 14:04.375
You think Dr. Al-Hashimi
can handle it?

14:04.376 --> 14:05.844
- In a word, no.

14:05.845 --> 14:07.378
- She's smart.

14:07.379 --> 14:08.613
- It takes more than that.

14:08.614 --> 14:10.348
- Yeah, well, at least

14:10.349 --> 14:11.649
it's only three months.

14:11.650 --> 14:13.785
- Yeah, three long months.

14:13.786 --> 14:15.553
Then you need to find
a new home.

14:15.554 --> 14:17.856
- [chuckles]
Not necessarily.

14:17.857 --> 14:19.891
I mean, if I wanted,
I could just check on

14:19.892 --> 14:22.894
Robby's house once
or twice a day, you know.

14:22.895 --> 14:24.797
- Why would you do that?

14:25.931 --> 14:28.299
- I don't know. Why not?

14:28.300 --> 14:31.269
[beeping, whirring]

14:31.270 --> 14:32.704
- Hypertonic's in.

14:32.705 --> 14:34.772
- Maintenance LR in the AC.

14:34.773 --> 14:36.541
- Looks like a halo sign.

14:36.542 --> 14:39.210
- Cerebrospinal fluid
from a basilar skull fracture.

14:39.211 --> 14:43.147
- The halo sign is neither
sensitive nor specific for CSF.

14:43.148 --> 14:45.516
Saline, tap water,
and runny noses

14:45.517 --> 14:46.684
all separate from blood.

14:46.685 --> 14:48.186
- Hello, Linda.
- Robby.

14:48.187 --> 14:50.688
- Division chief working
on a holiday weekend.

14:50.689 --> 14:52.824
- Well, somebody's got to.

14:52.825 --> 14:55.493
Saw the scans.
This guy needs an EVD.

14:55.494 --> 14:57.896
- External ventricular drain
to take down the pressure.

14:57.897 --> 15:01.132
- Because CPP equals
"MAP" minus ICP.

15:01.133 --> 15:03.835
- Cerebral perfusion pressure
in the brain

15:03.836 --> 15:05.737
equals mean arterial
blood pressure

15:05.738 --> 15:07.305
minus the pressure
in the skull.

15:07.306 --> 15:08.940
- ICP less than 22

15:08.941 --> 15:11.409
predicts survival
and favorable outcome.

15:11.410 --> 15:15.813
CPP from 60 to 70 reduces
morbidity and mortality.

15:15.814 --> 15:17.315
Can somebody assist?

15:17.316 --> 15:18.449
- Dr. Mohan?

15:18.450 --> 15:19.518
- I'm good.

15:20.719 --> 15:22.320
- Samira, you should
lend a hand.

15:22.321 --> 15:23.955
- I said I'm good.

15:23.956 --> 15:26.791
- Javadi?
- I don't think so.

15:26.792 --> 15:28.326
- Javadi?

15:28.327 --> 15:31.863
As in, daughter
of Raymond and Eileen?

15:31.864 --> 15:33.831
I was at your mother's
baby shower.

15:33.832 --> 15:35.333
[chuckles] She was a resident.

15:35.334 --> 15:36.568
You were in utero.

15:38.070 --> 15:39.137
I don't know how
she got through

15:39.138 --> 15:40.972
motherhood and training.

15:40.973 --> 15:42.507
Feel free to join me.

15:42.508 --> 15:44.509
- Oh, my--my shift was over
a while ago.

15:44.510 --> 15:45.944
- OK.

15:45.945 --> 15:48.079
Masks all around.
Two sterile gowns.

15:48.080 --> 15:50.515
We brought the surgical towels.
Just need some Betadine.

15:50.516 --> 15:52.284
- This is kind of
an amazing opportunity.

15:53.419 --> 15:54.752
- I'm exhausted.

15:54.753 --> 15:56.654
- The Chief of Neurosurgery
is here.

15:56.655 --> 15:58.089
She's kind of a legend.

15:58.090 --> 16:00.158
- Maybe one of the night
residents can do it.

16:00.159 --> 16:02.327
- Is this about
the volvulus case from earlier?

16:02.328 --> 16:03.928
'Cause if it is,
you made a mistake.

16:03.929 --> 16:05.964
You need to move on.

16:05.965 --> 16:07.465
I do not want to come back here
and find that

16:07.466 --> 16:10.802
you've applied
for a residency in derm.

16:10.803 --> 16:13.504
Step up to the plate. Do it.

16:13.505 --> 16:14.639
Javadi will assist.

16:14.640 --> 16:16.307
- Excellent.

16:16.308 --> 16:18.109
You know, I think Eileen did
her first EVD with me

16:18.110 --> 16:20.578
back when I was a brand-new
assistant professor.

16:20.579 --> 16:21.879
[scoffs]

16:21.880 --> 16:23.382
Time flies.

16:25.017 --> 16:26.217
- [raspy breathing]

16:26.218 --> 16:27.518
- How you doing, Grady?

16:27.519 --> 16:28.953
- Still retracting.

16:28.954 --> 16:30.655
- Any improvement?
- Not really.

16:30.656 --> 16:31.657
- You feeling tired?

16:33.525 --> 16:36.094
- Do we have Aerogen in the ED?
- Just in the unit.

16:36.095 --> 16:37.829
- How fast can you get back?

16:37.830 --> 16:38.863
- Two minutes
if I take the stairs.

16:38.864 --> 16:39.897
- Go.

16:39.898 --> 16:41.232
- Uh, Aerogen?

16:41.233 --> 16:43.267
- It has a 5-millimeter mesh

16:43.268 --> 16:46.472
that vibrates
over 120,000 times per second.

16:51.643 --> 16:53.078
- Dr. Al-Hashimi?

16:57.349 --> 16:58.650
- You OK?

17:01.153 --> 17:03.222
- Uh, you were telling us
about Aerogen.

17:04.223 --> 17:05.657
- Dr. Shen can explain.

17:07.159 --> 17:09.994
- It produces droplets
in the 2- to 5-micron range

17:09.995 --> 17:12.064
for medication delivery.

17:19.238 --> 17:21.839
- How's it going?
- Just about to start.

17:21.840 --> 17:22.974
- Securing the art line here.

17:22.975 --> 17:25.276
Measure twice, cut once.

17:25.277 --> 17:29.013
We enter 11 centimeters
back from the nasion,

17:29.014 --> 17:30.748
3 centimeters lateral.

17:30.749 --> 17:32.283
- Without any direct imaging?

17:32.284 --> 17:35.253
- No, straight shot
into the lateral ventricle--

17:35.254 --> 17:38.923
tried and true since 1890.

17:38.924 --> 17:41.260
OK, go ahead with the incision.

17:42.661 --> 17:44.896
- Hey, you worked
with Dr. Al-Hashimi at the VA.

17:44.897 --> 17:45.997
- I did.

17:45.998 --> 17:47.632
- For how long?

17:47.633 --> 17:49.634
- During my R2 rotation

17:49.635 --> 17:51.670
and then one again last year.

17:55.040 --> 17:58.209
- OK. Hand drill's all set.

17:58.210 --> 17:59.577
- Maybe you should do
this part.

17:59.578 --> 18:01.012
- No, no, there's
a safety stop here.

18:01.013 --> 18:02.613
You can't go too deep.

18:02.614 --> 18:04.550
It's not brain surgery.

18:06.718 --> 18:08.087
OK.

18:11.156 --> 18:12.957
Stay perpendicular.
- OK.

18:12.958 --> 18:14.992
- Good.

18:14.993 --> 18:16.794
All right, now, four turns

18:16.795 --> 18:17.929
to get through
the outer table...

18:17.930 --> 18:19.197
- Yep.
- Then half turns

18:19.198 --> 18:20.766
till you penetrate the skull.

18:24.570 --> 18:26.738
- [exhaling slowly]

18:31.677 --> 18:35.413
Three, four.

18:35.414 --> 18:36.582
One...

18:38.617 --> 18:40.284
- Holy smoke!

18:40.285 --> 18:43.788
I thought it was Tom Cruise
for a second over here.

18:43.789 --> 18:46.757
Nice job.
How's that feel, Digby?

18:46.758 --> 18:48.226
- Pretty good.
- I bet.

18:48.227 --> 18:49.527
What do you say we trim up

18:49.528 --> 18:51.396
those gorgeous locks
of yours now?

18:53.065 --> 18:55.166
- I don't like having
my hair cut.

18:55.167 --> 18:58.369
- I get it, Rapunzel,
but you need your ears lowered.

18:58.370 --> 19:00.471
You'll feel better
with a fresh summer look

19:00.472 --> 19:02.541
that won't go unnoticed
by the ladies.

19:04.376 --> 19:06.844
- Maybe just a trim?
- Great.

19:06.845 --> 19:09.046
I'm thinking a pixie cut.

19:09.047 --> 19:10.715
- What?
- I'm kidding.

19:10.716 --> 19:12.550
I cut my husband Benji's hair
all the time.

19:12.551 --> 19:14.152
Trust me, you're gonna look
fabulous.

19:14.153 --> 19:15.721
When's the last time
you had a haircut?

19:17.322 --> 19:20.625
- Maybe my daughter's wedding
a few years ago.

19:20.626 --> 19:21.926
- Where?

19:21.927 --> 19:23.161
- St. Sebastian,

19:23.162 --> 19:25.196
Our Lady of Mount Carmel
Parish.

19:25.197 --> 19:27.698
- Does your daughter know
where you are?

19:27.699 --> 19:31.002
- Of course.
We all live in Pittsburgh.

19:31.003 --> 19:33.272
In fact,
they live in my old house.

19:35.908 --> 19:38.042
- Your daughter lives
in your house?

19:38.043 --> 19:40.011
- Yep.

19:40.012 --> 19:42.647
- Where do you live?

19:42.648 --> 19:44.750
- Wherever I want.

19:46.485 --> 19:48.586
- You're gonna pass it
5 to 6 centimeters

19:48.587 --> 19:51.256
from the inner table
of the skull, OK?

19:53.058 --> 19:55.193
Centered...

19:55.194 --> 19:57.128
perpendicular...

19:57.129 --> 19:58.897
aiming for the medial canthus.

20:00.032 --> 20:01.799
All yours.

20:01.800 --> 20:03.134
- A-and just keep going?

20:03.135 --> 20:04.635
- You'll feel a pop
when you pass

20:04.636 --> 20:07.171
the ependymal lining.

20:07.172 --> 20:08.839
- Art line is calibrated.
Good to go.

20:08.840 --> 20:12.777
- Titrate the nicardipine
to a MAP of 85, please.

20:12.778 --> 20:14.178
- And if we can get
the intracranial pressure

20:14.179 --> 20:16.181
down to 20?

20:17.549 --> 20:18.916
Dr. Mohan?

20:18.917 --> 20:20.318
- I'm sorry.

20:20.319 --> 20:22.620
- MAP of 85, ICP of 20?

20:22.621 --> 20:25.623
- Um, cerebral perfusion
pressure 65.

20:25.624 --> 20:28.426
- Which gives him
the best shot at survival.

20:28.427 --> 20:29.994
A third of patients
like this die.

20:29.995 --> 20:32.530
Half have long-term disability.

20:32.531 --> 20:34.398
We'll know in two weeks
if there's a possibility

20:34.399 --> 20:36.834
for a good prognosis.

20:36.835 --> 20:38.035
- Felt a pop.

20:38.036 --> 20:39.638
- Remove the stylet.

20:42.140 --> 20:44.876
OK, let it drain a bit.

20:46.912 --> 20:49.214
And now pinch it shut.

20:50.616 --> 20:51.482
Perfect.

20:51.483 --> 20:53.584
- BP is down, 190 over 88.

20:53.585 --> 20:54.820
Heart rate's 67.

20:58.957 --> 21:00.958
- How are you guys doing?

21:00.959 --> 21:02.860
- Yeah, making some progress.

21:02.861 --> 21:04.128
- You seen Abbot?

21:04.129 --> 21:05.863
- Not since rounds.

21:05.864 --> 21:08.566
- He asked me to see a patient
with the night intern.

21:08.567 --> 21:10.301
- [yawning] And you said yes?

21:10.302 --> 21:13.271
- 48-year-old woman,
new onset jaundice,

21:13.272 --> 21:16.207
elevated liver enzymes,
no history of alcohol use.

21:16.208 --> 21:17.508
- Take your pick--

21:17.509 --> 21:20.311
hepatitis A, B, C, D, or E.

21:20.312 --> 21:23.214
- No risk factors, no fever.
- Tylenol?

21:23.215 --> 21:25.082
- Never,
and no prescription meds.

21:25.083 --> 21:27.352
- Does she eat
polar bear liver?

21:28.420 --> 21:30.689
It can cause
vitamin A toxicity.

21:31.690 --> 21:32.823
- No.
- Yeah.

21:32.824 --> 21:33.991
- She, uh, doesn't eat meat,

21:33.992 --> 21:35.526
kind of a health nut.

21:35.527 --> 21:37.094
- Well, maybe
she's gulping down

21:37.095 --> 21:38.729
cod liver oil
to prevent measles.

21:38.730 --> 21:40.798
- No. Vegan, no fish.

21:40.799 --> 21:42.967
Would you, uh, mind
laying eyes on her?

21:42.968 --> 21:44.568
- [sighs] Seriously?

21:44.569 --> 21:46.904
- You have a way of
figuring out the weird stuff.

21:46.905 --> 21:48.440
- Take the compliment.

21:49.775 --> 21:51.208
- OK, fine.

21:51.209 --> 21:53.477
Five minutes at the bedside--
that's it.

21:53.478 --> 21:55.313
I'm already gonna be here
for hours as it is.

21:55.314 --> 21:57.748
- Thank you.

21:57.749 --> 21:59.318
- What am I doing--

22:02.454 --> 22:04.889
- Definitely improving.
- Tidal volume's up.

22:04.890 --> 22:07.291
- Wheezes now expiratory only.

22:07.292 --> 22:08.959
- Oh, making some progress.

22:08.960 --> 22:10.895
- You feeling better, baby?

22:10.896 --> 22:14.298
You scared the shit out of me.
- Language!

22:14.299 --> 22:16.701
- Does he have
a primary-care doctor?

22:16.702 --> 22:17.902
- Not anymore.

22:17.903 --> 22:20.571
- How do you get
his prescriptions renewed?

22:20.572 --> 22:22.707
- Neighborhood clinic.
We pay cash.

22:22.708 --> 22:24.575
Albuterol's cheap.
- Symbicort?

22:24.576 --> 22:27.511
- Without Medicaid,
400 bucks a month.

22:27.512 --> 22:28.980
- Just for a little inhaler?

22:31.216 --> 22:33.651
- Trocar is on the tube.
[inhales deeply]

22:33.652 --> 22:37.021
I tunnel underneath the scalp
about 5 centimeters

22:37.022 --> 22:38.522
and poke through.

22:38.523 --> 22:40.359
- To prevent infection?
- Mm-hmm, exactly.

22:41.793 --> 22:44.463
Now you hold the knuckle steady
while I pull it through.

22:47.632 --> 22:49.835
And you can staple
the wound shut.

22:51.370 --> 22:53.471
- That looks like something
from Home Depot.

22:53.472 --> 22:55.339
- Yeah, big
Fourth of July sale.

22:55.340 --> 22:56.574
- The brain pressure
is measured by

22:56.575 --> 22:58.576
the height of the fluid column.

22:58.577 --> 23:01.112
We need to calibrate it to zero
at the level of the tragus.

23:01.113 --> 23:03.147
- Stopcock's on,
ready to attach.

23:03.148 --> 23:04.482
- First troponin's normal,

23:04.483 --> 23:06.851
but you need a second
to rule out MI.

23:06.852 --> 23:08.754
- Hey, can you step out
for a second?

23:14.793 --> 23:16.360
- I really did do
everything I could

23:16.361 --> 23:18.028
to try to make Orlando stay.

23:18.029 --> 23:19.029
- Yeah, I don't doubt it.

23:19.030 --> 23:20.030
I wanted to ask you about

23:20.031 --> 23:22.099
Dr. Al-Hashimi at the VA.

23:22.100 --> 23:24.902
Did you ever notice anything
unusual about her behavior?

23:24.903 --> 23:26.971
- Um, like what?

23:26.972 --> 23:29.507
- Lapses in focus, attention?

23:29.508 --> 23:32.010
- No, she was always
on top of her game.

23:35.013 --> 23:38.682
But this morning when she was
checking labs on Baby Jane Doe,

23:38.683 --> 23:41.019
it was like she zoned out
for a few seconds.

23:42.487 --> 23:44.423
Maybe she was just tired.

23:46.291 --> 23:48.993
- [inhales deeply]

23:48.994 --> 23:50.529
[sighs]

23:51.329 --> 23:53.764
- No congestion, nodules,

23:53.765 --> 23:55.166
or cirrhosis.

23:55.167 --> 23:56.934
- Good-looking liver.

23:56.935 --> 23:58.636
- I should not be sick.

23:58.637 --> 24:01.372
I work so hard
to stay healthy--

24:01.373 --> 24:04.141
diet, exercise,
eight hours of sleep.

24:04.142 --> 24:08.179
- I can't remember the last
time I got eight hours.

24:08.180 --> 24:10.147
- Maybe you should try
sleepmaxxing.

24:10.148 --> 24:11.949
- Oh, you definitely should.

24:11.950 --> 24:14.885
- Yeah, cold room,
white noise, eye shades.

24:14.886 --> 24:18.689
- Kiwis before bedtime,
lettuce water, mouth taping.

24:18.690 --> 24:20.491
- Who do you follow for health?

24:20.492 --> 24:22.726
- A few naturopaths
and some functional healers.

24:22.727 --> 24:24.695
- Do you--do you buy
vitamins from them?

24:24.696 --> 24:26.597
- Oh, no, no,
I don't take vitamins.

24:26.598 --> 24:29.400
Food is the best medicine--
kale, blueberries,

24:29.401 --> 24:31.869
kidney beans, turmeric.
- Turmeric?

24:31.870 --> 24:33.671
- Uh, how long have you
been taking that?

24:33.672 --> 24:36.140
- For a few months.
It's an anti-inflammatory.

24:36.141 --> 24:38.642
It detoxes the body,
and it can prevent Alzheimer's.

24:38.643 --> 24:40.244
- How much do you take?

24:40.245 --> 24:42.213
- 500 milligram capsules,

24:42.214 --> 24:43.548
but I take five a day.

24:45.116 --> 24:46.717
What?

24:46.718 --> 24:48.586
- With doses that large
of turmeric,

24:48.587 --> 24:51.222
there have been cases
of liver failure.

24:51.223 --> 24:52.890
- From eating a spice?

24:52.891 --> 24:55.559
- All right, Digby,
I think you're good to go.

24:55.560 --> 24:57.729
- Mm-hmm.
Would you like to see?

25:08.073 --> 25:09.207
- [sniffles]

25:10.375 --> 25:12.743
I haven't looked like this
in a long time.

25:12.744 --> 25:15.146
- Your family
won't recognize you.

25:17.182 --> 25:19.350
- Then how will they find me?

25:19.351 --> 25:21.318
They--they won't know
what I look like.

25:21.319 --> 25:22.353
They won't know this is me.

25:22.354 --> 25:23.454
- Of course they will.

25:23.455 --> 25:24.688
They know your voice.

25:24.689 --> 25:26.657
They know where you hang out.

25:26.658 --> 25:30.427
They even remember that
you used to look like this.

25:30.428 --> 25:32.531
They remember the wedding.

25:35.400 --> 25:37.568
- Did you dance
with your daughter

25:37.569 --> 25:39.037
at her wedding?

25:40.405 --> 25:42.673
- I did.

25:42.674 --> 25:45.777
- Then she will always
remember you.

25:48.413 --> 25:49.981
- Yeah.
- OK.

25:51.483 --> 25:53.183
- Hey, I was just
looking for you.

25:53.184 --> 25:54.485
- What's up?
- You tell me.

25:54.486 --> 25:56.754
The, uh, asthma patient.
- What about him?

25:56.755 --> 25:58.222
- Seemed like
you were hesitating

25:58.223 --> 25:59.857
talking about using Aerogen.

25:59.858 --> 26:01.492
I was wondering if you were
having second thoughts.

26:01.493 --> 26:03.260
- No. Just thinking.

26:03.261 --> 26:04.595
- About?

26:04.596 --> 26:06.530
- The best treatment plan
for the patient.

26:06.531 --> 26:08.632
And I think he's on it.

26:08.633 --> 26:10.100
Anything else?
- I don't know.

26:10.101 --> 26:12.670
You tell me.
Anything else I need to know?

26:12.671 --> 26:14.039
- I don't think so.

26:15.640 --> 26:17.274
- This is Dr. Robby in the ED.

26:17.275 --> 26:18.909
I'm checking on a patient,
Ekins.

26:18.910 --> 26:21.445
- We can take Larson
and Stevens off the dry-erase.

26:21.446 --> 26:22.513
- Consider it done.

26:22.514 --> 26:23.814
- He's in the scanner now?

26:23.815 --> 26:25.282
Oh, great.

26:25.283 --> 26:26.250
No, I was just calling
to confirm.

26:26.251 --> 26:27.585
Thank you.

26:27.586 --> 26:29.420
Any new information
from upstairs?

26:29.421 --> 26:30.721
- Nothing we don't
already know.

26:30.722 --> 26:32.556
- Same old story, huh?

26:32.557 --> 26:33.824
- You think we should
take up a collection

26:33.825 --> 26:35.659
for Jesse for--for bail money?

26:35.660 --> 26:37.194
- They don't usually set bail

26:37.195 --> 26:39.063
until after you've appeared
in front of a judge.

26:39.064 --> 26:40.898
- With the holiday, it's not
likely to happen till Monday.

26:40.899 --> 26:43.133
- So he's gonna be locked up
all weekend?

26:43.134 --> 26:44.935
- That sucks.

26:44.936 --> 26:46.837
- It does suck.

26:46.838 --> 26:49.873
- Dr. Langdon, Grady's worse--
much worse.

26:49.874 --> 26:52.610
- Need an attending?
- Uh, no, we have Shen.

26:52.611 --> 26:54.011
- Sat's down to 83.

26:54.012 --> 26:56.213
- What's happening?
- Give us a minute.

26:56.214 --> 26:57.715
- He's tiring out.

26:57.716 --> 26:59.650
Ketamine and rock.
It's time to intubate.

26:59.651 --> 27:00.851
- I'll call Volk.

27:00.852 --> 27:02.620
- Ma'am, we have to put a tube

27:02.621 --> 27:03.854
down your son's windpipe

27:03.855 --> 27:05.389
so a machine
can breathe for him.

27:05.390 --> 27:06.657
- [crying] Oh, my God.

27:06.658 --> 27:08.325
- Hold on, hold on.

27:08.326 --> 27:09.426
No lung sliding on the right.

27:09.427 --> 27:11.061
- Pneumothorax.

27:11.062 --> 27:13.097
- No need to intubate.

27:13.098 --> 27:14.331
- What's going on?

27:14.332 --> 27:16.333
- He has a collapsed lung.

27:16.334 --> 27:18.102
- There was no history
of trauma

27:18.103 --> 27:19.637
that would have caused
pneumothorax.

27:19.638 --> 27:21.739
- Glove up, Dr. King.

27:21.740 --> 27:24.008
- In asthma, you can get
"air trapping."

27:24.009 --> 27:25.743
When the lungs can't
fully exhale,

27:25.744 --> 27:27.144
eventually they overinflate,

27:27.145 --> 27:29.179
causing some of the tiny
air sacs to burst.

27:29.180 --> 27:30.314
- How do you fix it?

27:30.315 --> 27:33.284
[rapid beeping]

27:34.552 --> 27:36.220
[air whooshing]
- [gasping]

27:36.221 --> 27:37.188
- Like that.

27:42.827 --> 27:45.496
- It's a good thing
Dr. Conley was here.

27:45.497 --> 27:46.764
- Yeah.
- We should probably try

27:46.765 --> 27:48.198
to find him
a Neuro-Critical ICU bed.

27:48.199 --> 27:49.833
We don't want to board
a patient like this.

27:49.834 --> 27:51.602
- Mm-hmm.
- Hey, Robby.

27:51.603 --> 27:54.071
- Hey, how did the scan go?
- Fine.

27:54.072 --> 27:55.639
- It is probably gonna take
a little while

27:55.640 --> 27:56.974
to get the results
from the radiologist.

27:56.975 --> 27:58.575
- Well, that's not a problem.

27:58.576 --> 28:00.811
Nurse Vivi and I need
a little time

28:00.812 --> 28:03.347
to coordinate our schedules
over the next few months.

28:03.348 --> 28:04.381
- Really?
- Yeah.

28:04.382 --> 28:05.349
I've always wanted to learn

28:05.350 --> 28:06.417
how to ride a motorcycle,

28:06.418 --> 28:07.851
and Duke offered to teach me.

28:07.852 --> 28:10.120
- Well, nobody knows
motorcycles like Duke.

28:10.121 --> 28:12.589
- He's giving me the health
care worker discount.

28:12.590 --> 28:13.857
- He's quite the gentleman.

28:13.858 --> 28:15.726
Let's get him back to his room.

28:15.727 --> 28:18.562
- How would next Saturday be
for you, Vivi?

28:18.563 --> 28:21.799
Uh, maybe we could have
some dinner after.

28:21.800 --> 28:23.367
- Dr. Mohan,
Lorrie Diaz is here.

28:23.368 --> 28:25.269
She wants to see her husband.
She's heading back.

28:25.270 --> 28:26.805
- OK, I'm on my way.

28:28.807 --> 28:30.841
Mrs. Diaz?
- Hi.

28:30.842 --> 28:33.677
Did Orlando go up
to his room yet?

28:33.678 --> 28:35.212
- No. Um--

28:35.213 --> 28:37.414
- I brought him some dinner
from Burgatory.

28:37.415 --> 28:38.716
It's a chicken burger--

28:38.717 --> 28:40.317
no bun, just lettuce.

28:40.318 --> 28:43.088
Figured it would be better
than hospital food.

28:46.324 --> 28:50.594
- He's being treated by our top
brain-injury specialists.

28:50.595 --> 28:52.062
- Will he wake up?

28:52.063 --> 28:53.997
- We won't know
for several weeks.

28:53.998 --> 28:56.700
- And then he could be
back to normal?

28:56.701 --> 28:59.770
- Best-case scenario,
it would take about a year

28:59.771 --> 29:02.406
before he could be
independent at home.

29:02.407 --> 29:04.041
- And the worst case?

29:04.042 --> 29:07.412
- Round-the-clock nursing care
for severe disability.

29:11.182 --> 29:13.250
- You let him leave?

29:13.251 --> 29:17.387
- He insisted on leaving
to work at his second job.

29:17.388 --> 29:19.590
- You couldn't make him stay?

29:19.591 --> 29:22.593
- He was competent.
He knew the risks.

29:22.594 --> 29:24.561
We honored his decision
to leave.

29:24.562 --> 29:26.363
- Even if it was a stupid one?

29:26.364 --> 29:27.865
- I tried to stop him.

29:27.866 --> 29:29.500
Offered to get him
all the supplies he'd need

29:29.501 --> 29:30.934
to take care of himself
at home.

29:30.935 --> 29:33.403
But he left before
I could give them to him.

29:33.404 --> 29:35.974
He said he couldn't afford
to lose a paycheck.

29:43.448 --> 29:45.649
- Dr. Langdon.

29:45.650 --> 29:46.818
[door closes]

29:47.786 --> 29:49.653
Are you OK?

29:49.654 --> 29:52.823
- Yeah. I'm just kind of, uh...

29:52.824 --> 29:55.325
wondering if I'm really
ready to be back here.

29:55.326 --> 29:57.561
- Well, of course you are.

29:57.562 --> 29:59.696
- Ten months is a long time.

29:59.697 --> 30:02.933
I almost killed that kid
with an intubation.

30:02.934 --> 30:06.136
Didn't even occur to me
to check for pneumothorax.

30:06.137 --> 30:07.905
- There wasn't any trauma
to indicate--

30:07.906 --> 30:09.107
- I should have caught it.
- OK.

30:11.776 --> 30:13.444
- [sighs]

30:15.747 --> 30:17.214
- You know, I, um...

30:17.215 --> 30:18.916
[chair scraping]

30:18.917 --> 30:21.952
I had a deposition today,

30:21.953 --> 30:25.289
and all the lawyer's questions
made me feel like

30:25.290 --> 30:27.792
I was a really,
really bad doctor.

30:30.094 --> 30:33.498
We don't always get everything
right the first time.

30:34.732 --> 30:37.267
You would have caught
the collapsed lung.

30:37.268 --> 30:39.971
And it may have taken a minute,
but you would have saved him.

30:41.105 --> 30:43.540
- I'm not sure
Robby would agree with you.

30:43.541 --> 30:46.210
He's been riding me all day.

30:46.211 --> 30:48.078
- Well, Robby's leaving
for three months.

30:48.079 --> 30:50.948
And, you know,
with Robby gone...

30:50.949 --> 30:52.984
I really don't want you
to leave either.

30:56.421 --> 30:59.056
That which does not kill me
makes me stronger.

30:59.057 --> 31:02.492
- Wow, Friedrich Nietzsche.

31:02.493 --> 31:05.629
- Yeah, Nietzsche, yeah...

31:05.630 --> 31:07.865
not Kelly Clarkson.

31:07.866 --> 31:09.900
- [chuckles]

31:09.901 --> 31:11.969
- Hey, that's a thick one.

31:11.970 --> 31:14.771
- Yeah, Austin Green.
Ogilvie's triple-A.

31:14.772 --> 31:17.741
[beeping, whirring]

31:17.742 --> 31:20.544
- Uh, G-R-E-E-N?

31:20.545 --> 31:21.879
- Yeah. Why?
What are you doing?

31:21.880 --> 31:23.380
- Checking to see
when we'll get Ogilvie

31:23.381 --> 31:25.315
back from the OR.

31:25.316 --> 31:27.384
Oh, shit.
- What?

31:27.385 --> 31:29.019
- The guy didn't make it.

31:29.020 --> 31:31.388
He died on the table
about 40 minutes ago.

31:31.389 --> 31:33.490
- Then where's Ogilvie?

31:33.491 --> 31:35.392
- Oh, man.

31:35.393 --> 31:38.028
His patient had a CT
a year and a half ago

31:38.029 --> 31:40.264
that showed
a 4-centimeter triple-A.

31:40.265 --> 31:41.999
- That's too small for surgery.

31:42.000 --> 31:43.300
- He was supposed
to come back

31:43.301 --> 31:45.068
every six months
for a repeat ultrasound,

31:45.069 --> 31:46.937
but looks like he didn't.

31:46.938 --> 31:49.573
- We would've seen that
if the computers were working.

31:49.574 --> 31:51.208
Why wouldn't he tell Ogilvie?

31:51.209 --> 31:53.043
- [sighing] I don't know.
Maybe he forgot all about it.

31:53.044 --> 31:55.113
Or Ogilvie didn't ask
the right questions.

31:56.080 --> 31:58.115
- Dennis, hey, got a minute?

31:58.116 --> 32:00.751
- Uh, sure. What do you need?

32:00.752 --> 32:02.319
- Teenager with jewelry magnets

32:02.320 --> 32:04.354
stuck to both sides
of her nasal septum.

32:04.355 --> 32:06.323
I tried to move them
with a plastic curette.

32:06.324 --> 32:08.258
Too much pain,
and then there was bleeding.

32:08.259 --> 32:10.460
- Those need to come off before
they cause permanent damage.

32:10.461 --> 32:12.029
- Yeah, you think, uh,
you could find, like,

32:12.030 --> 32:14.064
a senior or an attending?

32:14.065 --> 32:15.866
We're really trying
to get off the clock here.

32:15.867 --> 32:17.101
- They're all busy.

32:19.804 --> 32:21.405
- I already took one
for the team.

32:21.406 --> 32:23.240
- Yeah, fine.

32:23.241 --> 32:26.843
- Uh, labs on your yellow lady.

32:26.844 --> 32:29.279
- INR is elevated, 2.2.

32:29.280 --> 32:31.214
- Liver's in trouble
but not dead yet.

32:31.215 --> 32:32.950
- Tell her to skip
the turmeric.

32:32.951 --> 32:34.985
Admit for monitoring,
and follow the LFTs.

32:34.986 --> 32:36.153
- Got it.
- Mm-hmm.

32:36.154 --> 32:37.622
- Central 10?
- Yeah.

32:41.993 --> 32:44.161
- "Sleepmaxxing"? Really?

32:44.162 --> 32:45.862
- I track the online trends.

32:45.863 --> 32:48.298
- Is that your secret
for the tough ones?

32:48.299 --> 32:50.000
- I just think,

32:50.001 --> 32:52.169
what's the stupidest thing
this person could have done?

32:52.170 --> 32:53.471
Then assume they did it.

32:54.973 --> 32:57.107
- Well, I mean,
she was trying to be healthy.

32:57.108 --> 32:59.409
- Yeah, by taking advice
from fools.

32:59.410 --> 33:01.545
- Turmeric is recommended
by a lot of doctors.

33:01.546 --> 33:03.547
- Yeah, then ask your doctor
for the dose

33:03.548 --> 33:06.283
or check someplace reputable,
like the CDC.

33:06.284 --> 33:09.453
Oh, right, I forgot, it's now
a medical toxic waste site.

33:09.454 --> 33:12.556
- I mean,
she's in pretty bad shape.

33:12.557 --> 33:14.958
If things get worse, she could
need a liver transplant.

33:14.959 --> 33:17.061
- Yeah, 'cause she's a big
fucking idiot.

33:18.496 --> 33:20.263
- Wow.

33:20.264 --> 33:22.566
- No, I actually
appreciate her.

33:22.567 --> 33:25.336
Our job security depends on
all these big fucking idiots.

33:27.705 --> 33:29.040
- OK.

33:31.242 --> 33:34.811
- Uh, good night,
Perlah, Monica.

33:34.812 --> 33:37.514
Good night, Dr. Robby.
- Good night.

33:37.515 --> 33:39.049
- Bye, Emma.

33:39.050 --> 33:40.450
- You could stay to pitch in.

33:40.451 --> 33:42.552
- Mm, Dana told me
to go and get some rest

33:42.553 --> 33:43.920
before tomorrow's shift.

33:43.921 --> 33:45.622
- Yeah, you had quite a day.

33:45.623 --> 33:47.025
- Wasn't so bad.

33:48.960 --> 33:50.794
- Why can't I find
Duke's results?

33:50.795 --> 33:53.463
- Oh, new patient, no EHR yet.

33:53.464 --> 33:56.199
- I can run over to Radiology,
get a printout.

33:56.200 --> 33:57.635
- Thank you, Monica.

34:00.171 --> 34:02.172
- Ready to pick up a few more.

34:02.173 --> 34:03.540
Orlando's all tucked in
for now.

34:03.541 --> 34:05.342
- How's he doing?
- Numbers are good.

34:05.343 --> 34:07.177
CPP 22.

34:07.178 --> 34:09.746
- OK, so he's got a shot
at a decent outcome at least.

34:09.747 --> 34:11.314
- You think he has a chance?

34:11.315 --> 34:13.650
- Oh, I don't know
that survival was

34:13.651 --> 34:15.552
the outcome he was hoping for.

34:15.553 --> 34:17.220
- What?

34:17.221 --> 34:19.356
- He told Samira he's got
$100,000 in medical debt,

34:19.357 --> 34:21.759
that his life is probably--
- Mrs. Diaz!

34:24.162 --> 34:26.563
How can we help you?
- The bathroom?

34:26.564 --> 34:29.333
- Uh, yeah.
Perlah can show you the way.

34:31.102 --> 34:33.437
Not a great idea to have
a private conversation

34:33.438 --> 34:34.738
about a patient
in a public area.

34:34.739 --> 34:36.807
- I know. I know.

34:36.808 --> 34:38.075
- You were
about to start yapping--

34:38.076 --> 34:39.610
- But I didn't!

34:42.280 --> 34:45.148
- OK.

34:45.149 --> 34:47.551
And how long have they
been in there?

34:47.552 --> 34:48.985
- At least two hours.

34:48.986 --> 34:51.354
- How did it happen?
- With my earring.

34:51.355 --> 34:54.224
It was supposed to be, uh,
red, white, and blue

34:54.225 --> 34:56.093
to look cool at the fireworks.

34:56.094 --> 34:57.794
- I told her for the nose,
one side only,

34:57.795 --> 34:59.029
but she never listens.

34:59.030 --> 35:00.230
- This can be pretty serious.

35:00.231 --> 35:01.465
If we don't get them out
quickly,

35:01.466 --> 35:03.033
it can cut off the blood supply

35:03.034 --> 35:04.968
and cause the septum
to collapse.

35:04.969 --> 35:08.473
- Like, my nose
could be deformed?

35:10.641 --> 35:13.310
Oh, my God, get them off.
- Yeah, that's the plan.

35:13.311 --> 35:15.045
- Yeah, she tried already.
It hurt like crazy.

35:15.046 --> 35:16.179
- Because they're
stuck together

35:16.180 --> 35:18.215
by a very strong
magnetic force.

35:18.216 --> 35:20.217
- Yeah.
- No, no, no.

35:20.218 --> 35:22.018
- Oh, uh, I'm not gonna
use the tips.

35:22.019 --> 35:24.988
I'm gonna flip it around
and use the handle.

35:24.989 --> 35:26.656
- It's still gonna hurt.

35:26.657 --> 35:27.858
- Probably not.

35:27.859 --> 35:29.260
Just, uh, hold still.

35:31.696 --> 35:33.231
OK.

35:36.501 --> 35:38.768
[sighs] Voilà.

35:38.769 --> 35:41.338
- Really?
- That was amazing.

35:41.339 --> 35:43.273
- I think another half hour,

35:43.274 --> 35:44.908
we can send this dry-erase
board back to storage.

35:44.909 --> 35:46.109
- With pleasure.

35:46.110 --> 35:47.644
- Dr. Robinavitch?
- Yep.

35:47.645 --> 35:49.080
- Results on your friend.

35:53.684 --> 35:55.753
- Fuck.
- Duke?

35:59.790 --> 36:01.424
Are you gonna tell him?

36:01.425 --> 36:03.160
- I want to talk
to a surgeon first.

36:03.161 --> 36:05.095
- Uh, Dr. Robby, I have
an update on the patient.

36:05.096 --> 36:06.496
- Now is not a great time.

36:06.497 --> 36:07.931
- Oh, I thought
you were going home.

36:07.932 --> 36:09.132
- Uh, I was.

36:09.133 --> 36:11.001
Dr. Ogilvie is just sitting

36:11.002 --> 36:12.602
out in the ambulance bay
covered in blood.

36:12.603 --> 36:14.304
- Sorry, what--
what's he doing out there?

36:14.305 --> 36:16.273
- Kind of, uh,
staring off into space.

36:16.274 --> 36:17.474
I tried to talk to him,
but it was like

36:17.475 --> 36:19.042
he couldn't hear me.
- Monica,

36:19.043 --> 36:20.544
can you stat page
CardioThoracic?

36:20.545 --> 36:22.713
- I'll go check on Ogilvie.
- Please.

36:25.016 --> 36:26.350
- Oh.

36:34.425 --> 36:37.727
[sighs]

36:37.728 --> 36:39.830
Hey, Ogilvie.

36:42.533 --> 36:44.534
Ogilvie...

36:44.535 --> 36:46.370
y-you OK, man?

36:49.774 --> 36:51.274
[sighs]

36:51.275 --> 36:53.476
- 99 on 2 liters.

36:53.477 --> 36:55.879
- Scattered end
expiratory wheezes.

36:55.880 --> 36:58.081
- He is so much better.

36:58.082 --> 37:00.116
- The steroids
should kick in soon.

37:00.117 --> 37:02.385
- So he'll keep improving.

37:02.386 --> 37:04.854
- Um, when can I go home?

37:04.855 --> 37:06.523
- In a day or two.

37:06.524 --> 37:09.859
And we will, uh, discharge you
with a Symbicort inhaler.

37:09.860 --> 37:11.861
That should last about a month.

37:11.862 --> 37:14.397
- Hopefully we'll be
back on Medicaid by then.

37:14.398 --> 37:16.566
- How'd you lose it?

37:16.567 --> 37:20.036
- They sent a redetermination
letter to our old apartment.

37:20.037 --> 37:22.539
It didn't get forwarded.

37:22.540 --> 37:24.608
When I went to pick up
his prescription,

37:24.609 --> 37:28.511
pharmacist told me
we were no longer covered.

37:28.512 --> 37:30.814
- And you haven't been able
to get it back since?

37:30.815 --> 37:33.116
- I've been trying for months.

37:33.117 --> 37:35.585
To get re-enrolled,
you need tax returns,

37:35.586 --> 37:36.987
pay stubs.

37:36.988 --> 37:39.756
I cut hair.
My income fluctuates.

37:39.757 --> 37:42.259
A lot of my regulars
are struggling,

37:42.260 --> 37:45.395
so it's been tough.

37:45.396 --> 37:47.397
- Well, if you run out
of Symbicort

37:47.398 --> 37:49.666
before your Medicaid kicks in,
you can come back,

37:49.667 --> 37:52.602
and we'll, uh, set you up
with another one.

37:52.603 --> 37:54.671
- Oh, is there
a patient in here?

37:54.672 --> 37:57.707
'Cause everyone in this room
looks extremely healthy to me.

37:57.708 --> 38:00.210
- Dr. Shen and I will be
with Grady all night long.

38:00.211 --> 38:02.212
- Yeah. Day shift, we got this.

38:02.213 --> 38:04.047
- We're leaving you
in good hands.

38:04.048 --> 38:05.982
- Um...

38:05.983 --> 38:08.285
I was really scared.

38:08.286 --> 38:09.587
Thank you.

38:11.188 --> 38:13.324
- You're very welcome.

38:17.194 --> 38:19.730
- Due to his injury,
things have changed.

38:21.198 --> 38:23.433
- I was looking for Dr. Abbot.

38:23.434 --> 38:26.236
- I haven't seen him
for a while.

38:26.237 --> 38:27.605
- Excuse me.

38:29.240 --> 38:30.573
[door opens]

38:30.574 --> 38:32.509
- So now,
with a long-term disability,

38:32.510 --> 38:35.245
things may be easier.

38:35.246 --> 38:36.446
- "Easier"?

38:36.447 --> 38:38.014
- His condition
will qualify him

38:38.015 --> 38:39.482
for Medicare and Medicaid.

38:39.483 --> 38:42.018
So, moving forward,
costs should be covered,

38:42.019 --> 38:43.787
including home health care.

38:43.788 --> 38:45.188
- OK.

38:45.189 --> 38:46.523
- Perhaps this isn't
the best time--

38:46.524 --> 38:47.991
- I just wanted to reassure you

38:47.992 --> 38:49.794
about future costs.

38:57.968 --> 38:59.536
- Robby.

38:59.537 --> 39:01.504
- Noelle.

39:01.505 --> 39:03.340
- You're still here.

39:03.341 --> 39:05.642
- It's not the best day
to try to get out on time.

39:05.643 --> 39:07.277
- Mm.

39:07.278 --> 39:08.611
So I guess this is it
for a while.

39:08.612 --> 39:10.180
- Unless you want
to come with me.

39:10.181 --> 39:12.549
- No, but thank you,

39:12.550 --> 39:14.584
even if it isn't
a legitimate offer.

39:14.585 --> 39:16.186
- What do you mean?
- Oh, please.

39:16.187 --> 39:18.054
I know well enough
not to get in between

39:18.055 --> 39:19.990
a man and his vision quest.

39:21.392 --> 39:22.726
- "Vision quest."

39:22.727 --> 39:25.896
- That is my nice way
of putting it.

39:27.164 --> 39:28.498
- I probably don't want to hear

39:28.499 --> 39:30.333
your not-so-nice way
of putting it.

39:30.334 --> 39:31.769
- No, probably not.

39:33.471 --> 39:37.140
I-I hope that
this is not, um...

39:37.141 --> 39:38.408
about you running away from me.

39:38.409 --> 39:39.642
I'm a big girl.

39:39.643 --> 39:41.378
You can tell me
just to get lost.

39:41.379 --> 39:43.179
- This has nothing
to do with you.

39:43.180 --> 39:44.514
- Oh, right.

39:44.515 --> 39:47.351
It's the old, uh,
"it's not you, it's me"?

39:48.686 --> 39:50.888
- In this case,
it's actually true.

39:57.094 --> 39:58.763
- Excuse me.

40:04.902 --> 40:06.236
- I'll see you next week?

40:06.237 --> 40:07.537
- It's a three-month
sabbatical.

40:07.538 --> 40:09.573
- Like I said,
I will see you next week.

40:16.247 --> 40:19.416
- My first day here
as a med student...

40:19.417 --> 40:21.151
there was a patient.

40:21.152 --> 40:22.986
[sighs]

40:22.987 --> 40:24.587
He was a real nice guy,

40:24.588 --> 40:27.524
came in with belly pain.

40:27.525 --> 40:31.161
I saw a gall stone
on the ultrasound,

40:31.162 --> 40:33.396
normal EKG, troponin.

40:33.397 --> 40:36.633
The pain resolved,
and he was in the hall

40:36.634 --> 40:38.636
when he had a cardiac arrest.

40:41.338 --> 40:42.773
I couldn't save him.

40:44.275 --> 40:45.776
People die.

40:47.244 --> 40:50.814
And we do the best we can...

40:50.815 --> 40:53.083
but people die.

40:54.351 --> 40:56.420
- You ever get used to it?

40:57.922 --> 40:59.523
- [chuckles] No.

41:00.891 --> 41:03.593
No, you...

41:03.594 --> 41:05.629
you try to accept it.

41:07.498 --> 41:09.433
You try to find balance.

41:14.772 --> 41:17.708
- I don't know if I can take
another day like today.

41:19.310 --> 41:22.479
Primary care specialty
sounds way better.

41:22.480 --> 41:24.347
Pedes, maybe.

41:24.348 --> 41:25.916
- Yeah, maybe.

41:27.518 --> 41:30.654
I know I'd be bored
out of my fucking mind.

41:31.889 --> 41:35.925
Seriously, I like the challenge
of undiagnosed illness,

41:35.926 --> 41:40.864
of quick decisions,
of life-saving procedures.

41:40.865 --> 41:43.433
And I like being here
for people

41:43.434 --> 41:45.803
on the worst days
of their lives.

41:50.541 --> 41:51.909
[clears throat]

41:54.011 --> 41:56.012
You know what I think?

41:56.013 --> 41:57.647
- What?

41:57.648 --> 42:00.116
- I think you should go home.

42:00.117 --> 42:01.484
I think you should sleep on it.

42:01.485 --> 42:03.052
And I think you should
at least wait

42:03.053 --> 42:04.220
till the morning to decide

42:04.221 --> 42:05.689
if you want to come back.

42:08.592 --> 42:10.894
- I don't really want to...

42:10.895 --> 42:13.730
go back in there
and see anybody.

42:13.731 --> 42:14.798
- Yeah.

42:16.367 --> 42:18.935
OK, pull off your gown.
I'll take it in.

42:18.936 --> 42:21.271
Shift is over.

42:21.272 --> 42:22.840
Go home.

42:24.675 --> 42:27.845
[indistinct chatter]

42:33.951 --> 42:37.086
- Oh!
- [gasps] Oh, God.

42:37.087 --> 42:38.187
- No, I'm--I'm--
- Sorry.

42:38.188 --> 42:39.522
- I'm good. I'm good. I'm good.

42:39.523 --> 42:41.291
- There's a dummy
in a wheelchair.

42:41.292 --> 42:43.093
- Uh, yeah, he moves around.

42:46.230 --> 42:48.431
I see I've been replaced.

42:48.432 --> 42:49.866
- Oh, did I take your spot?

42:49.867 --> 42:51.601
- Not really, no.
- Are you sure?

42:51.602 --> 42:53.136
- Where the hell have you been?

42:53.137 --> 42:54.804
- I found Ogilvie.

42:54.805 --> 42:56.072
- And?

42:56.073 --> 42:58.308
- And he's going home.

42:58.309 --> 42:59.509
- That's it?

42:59.510 --> 43:00.810
- It's a long story.

43:00.811 --> 43:02.412
- Well, I got nothing but time.

43:02.413 --> 43:04.514
- I need to respect
his privacy.

43:04.515 --> 43:06.015
- Where's the fun in that?

43:06.016 --> 43:08.052
- Beep. Beep, beep. [chuckles]
- Sorry.

43:09.320 --> 43:11.288
[whirring]

43:16.594 --> 43:17.994
- Um, the shredder jammed.

43:17.995 --> 43:21.130
- Yeah, uh, try
putting it in reverse.

43:21.131 --> 43:23.366
[whirring]

43:23.367 --> 43:24.634
- Perfect.

43:24.635 --> 43:26.669
- Just give it
a little love tap.

43:26.670 --> 43:28.271
- OK.
- Kick it.

43:28.272 --> 43:29.372
[banging]

43:29.373 --> 43:31.074
Jesus Christ.

43:31.075 --> 43:32.909
[laughter]

43:32.910 --> 43:35.144
- Guess Mr. Digby got
a room upstairs.

43:35.145 --> 43:36.546
- In your dreams.

43:36.547 --> 43:38.514
- He's not in South 21.

43:38.515 --> 43:39.916
- Yeah, he is.

43:39.917 --> 43:42.352
- There's a new guy in the bed.

43:42.353 --> 43:44.354
- Short hair, clean-shaved?

43:44.355 --> 43:46.756
I'll take care of it.

43:46.757 --> 43:48.491
- Scout film showed
obvious pathology,

43:48.492 --> 43:49.926
so we ordered the CT angiogram.

43:49.927 --> 43:51.594
- Textbook ascending
aortic aneurysm.

43:51.595 --> 43:53.496
Eight centimeters.

43:53.497 --> 43:55.431
50% one-year mortality.

43:55.432 --> 43:56.633
- So he definitely needs
surgery.

43:56.634 --> 43:57.634
- If he wants to live.

43:57.635 --> 43:58.668
- OK, well, he's a friend,

43:58.669 --> 43:59.969
so I will talk to him.

43:59.970 --> 44:01.237
I'll get him admitted
to your service.

44:01.238 --> 44:03.239
- Not today.
- Why not?

44:03.240 --> 44:05.208
- He needs to see Cardiology
and Pulmonary first

44:05.209 --> 44:06.476
to be cleared for the OR.

44:06.477 --> 44:08.277
They can do a stress echo,
PFTs.

44:08.278 --> 44:10.647
- He needs to be admitted
and evaluated as an inpatient.

44:10.648 --> 44:12.315
- Nothing ever gets done
over a holiday weekend.

44:12.316 --> 44:13.383
He can take it easy at home.

44:13.384 --> 44:14.784
- He's a ticking time bomb.

44:14.785 --> 44:16.019
- He's probably been that way
for years.

44:16.020 --> 44:17.453
We can get him in
early next week

44:17.454 --> 44:18.955
with a specialist
to get his testing done.

44:18.956 --> 44:20.890
All goes well, he's on
the OR schedule in a week.

44:20.891 --> 44:22.492
- What happens if
it ruptures before then?

44:22.493 --> 44:24.427
- Call 911.

44:24.428 --> 44:26.029
Sorry, Robby. Best we can do.

44:26.030 --> 44:27.998
Text me his number.
I'll have my office coordinate.

44:30.234 --> 44:31.734
- Fuck!
- Hey!

44:31.735 --> 44:33.637
Take a walk. Come on!

44:36.940 --> 44:38.708
[bell dings]
- Two for discharge.

44:38.709 --> 44:40.209
- Yeah, please don't
ring the bell.

44:40.210 --> 44:41.844
The computers are
back up and running.

44:41.845 --> 44:43.379
- Not for these two.

44:43.380 --> 44:44.781
They don't have electronic
health records yet.

44:44.782 --> 44:46.182
- Wait, hold up.

44:46.183 --> 44:48.518
This kid had
a wrist X-ray ordered.

44:48.519 --> 44:49.752
Ugh, it never happened.

44:49.753 --> 44:51.020
And water-skiing lady's

44:51.021 --> 44:52.455
still waiting on a knee series.

44:52.456 --> 44:53.723
- I canceled the X-rays.

44:53.724 --> 44:56.092
Diagnosed them both
with ultrasound.

44:56.093 --> 44:57.293
- Really?

44:57.294 --> 44:59.028
- Yeah.

44:59.029 --> 45:01.564
The, uh, little boy had
a simple buckle fracture.

45:01.565 --> 45:04.133
Distal radius.
He got a Velcro splint.

45:04.134 --> 45:06.903
And Mrs. Stegman had
a small medial meniscus tear.

45:06.904 --> 45:09.205
Knee immobilizer, crutches,
and a follow up with ortho.

45:09.206 --> 45:11.507
- Could have used you
on the day shift today.

45:11.508 --> 45:14.077
- They don't teach us a lot
of musculoskeletal ultrasound.

45:14.078 --> 45:15.445
- I know.

45:15.446 --> 45:18.181
That's why I did electives
at Harvard and Highland.

45:18.182 --> 45:20.983
- Are you applying for
an ultrasound fellowship here?

45:20.984 --> 45:23.853
- I am,
but it is so competitive.

45:23.854 --> 45:25.988
- That's what I hear.
- Kind of a long shot.

45:25.989 --> 45:27.590
I only have one publication,

45:27.591 --> 45:29.325
but it's a series
of case reports diagnosing

45:29.326 --> 45:31.961
shoulder dislocations
with ultrasound only.

45:31.962 --> 45:33.863
If you want to learn some MSK,
you can tag along.

45:33.864 --> 45:35.465
I got three more to scan.

45:35.466 --> 45:37.400
- Maybe some other time.

45:37.401 --> 45:39.769
- Cool.

45:39.770 --> 45:42.105
[whirring]

45:42.106 --> 45:44.273
- Hey, don't jam the shredder.

45:44.274 --> 45:45.808
What is that, two charts?

45:45.809 --> 45:48.245
- No, it's my ultrasound
fellowship application.

45:50.114 --> 45:51.714
- Hey.

45:51.715 --> 45:54.751
Uh, sorry about your patient.

45:54.752 --> 45:57.720
- Yeah, Orlando's
in pretty bad shape.

45:57.721 --> 45:59.689
- Oh, no,
I--I was talking about

45:59.690 --> 46:03.292
the triple-A guy
you worked on with Ogilvie.

46:03.293 --> 46:04.361
[sighs]

46:05.863 --> 46:08.531
He didn't make it
through surgery.

46:08.532 --> 46:09.932
I tried to talk to Robby
about it,

46:09.933 --> 46:12.101
but I think he's busy.

46:12.102 --> 46:13.771
- Excuse me.

46:15.906 --> 46:17.908
- [sighing] Oh, shit.

46:21.945 --> 46:23.646
- You think I'm on edge?

46:23.647 --> 46:25.214
First you're shaming Samira,
then McKay--

46:25.215 --> 46:26.682
- They both needed
to be called out

46:26.683 --> 46:27.984
for unacceptable behavior.
- Yeah?

46:27.985 --> 46:29.218
Yeah, well, you do that
in private.

46:29.219 --> 46:30.753
Same place
you share your thoughts

46:30.754 --> 46:31.888
about a patient's
possible suicide.

46:31.889 --> 46:33.322
And slamming stuff? Please.

46:33.323 --> 46:34.590
Sign out all the shit
that's bugging you

46:34.591 --> 46:35.758
and get out of here.

46:35.759 --> 46:37.693
- I can't.
- Yes, you can.

46:37.694 --> 46:38.928
When either of my kids
was acting like this,

46:38.929 --> 46:40.329
I gave them a time-out
in their room.

46:40.330 --> 46:41.564
- Whoa, whoa, whoa,
you're not my mother.

46:41.565 --> 46:42.765
- Yeah? Well, too bad.

46:42.766 --> 46:43.933
You need one.
- No, I had one.

46:43.934 --> 46:45.568
She left.
I don't need another one.

46:45.569 --> 46:46.969
What I need is someone
who can actually run this place

46:46.970 --> 46:48.905
while I'm gone.
- OK, I'm sorry.

46:48.906 --> 46:50.206
I didn't know.
- Nobody knows.

46:50.207 --> 46:52.608
Who needs to know?
Who gives a fuck?

46:52.609 --> 46:53.910
- I think you need a break.

46:53.911 --> 46:55.545
- That is what
the sabbatical is for.

46:55.546 --> 46:56.946
- Then start it now. Walk away.

46:56.947 --> 46:58.214
- I have too much to do.

46:58.215 --> 46:59.949
- Let someone else
talk to Duke.

46:59.950 --> 47:01.684
- No, that needs
to come from me.

47:01.685 --> 47:03.019
- Why?

47:03.020 --> 47:04.554
- Because I owe him that.

47:04.555 --> 47:06.455
It needs to come from a friend,
not a stranger,

47:06.456 --> 47:08.591
otherwise he's gonna bail
and drop dead while I'm gone.

47:08.592 --> 47:11.460
- OK, wrap that up
and then leave.

47:11.461 --> 47:13.062
- It's not just Duke.

47:13.063 --> 47:14.864
I'm not sure that Al-Hashimi
is fit to run this place.

47:14.865 --> 47:15.965
- What's that supposed to mean?
- I'm not sure.

47:15.966 --> 47:17.533
I'm trying to figure that out.

47:17.534 --> 47:18.835
Did you know that she wants
to have two attendings

47:18.836 --> 47:20.436
on at all times?
- No.

47:20.437 --> 47:22.004
- Is that something
she's worked out with Gloria?

47:22.005 --> 47:23.606
- I don't know.
- I also don't know

47:23.607 --> 47:24.907
if Langdon is going to relapse.

47:24.908 --> 47:25.842
I don't know if
Whitaker's gonna be able

47:25.843 --> 47:27.243
to take care of my shit.

47:27.244 --> 47:28.911
I don't know if
Javadi's gonna give up on

47:28.912 --> 47:30.780
what she's good at
or if Samira's gonna flame out

47:30.781 --> 47:32.114
because of some bullshit
with her mother.

47:32.115 --> 47:34.650
- Is there anything else?
- Yeah, you.

47:34.651 --> 47:36.853
I don't know about you
running around

47:36.854 --> 47:38.487
with a full syringe of Versed
in your pocket.

47:38.488 --> 47:40.924
I'm worried about the people
that I care about.
